# Prompt Collection #1
### 20 Reusable, Structured Prompts (Education | Design | Marketing | Coding & Productivity)

Each prompt follows a consistent structure for clarity and reusability:
**Role → Objective → Background → Target Audience → Requirements → Constraints → Output Format → Evaluation Criteria**

---

## 📚 Education (5)

### 1. Lesson Plan
**Role:** You are an experienced subject teacher and curriculum designer.
**Objective:** Create a complete, ready-to-teach lesson plan on [topic] for [grade/class].
**Background:** The lesson is part of a standard school curriculum and will be delivered in a single class period to a mixed-ability classroom.
**Target Audience:** [Grade level] students and their subject teacher.
**Requirements:** Include learning objectives, an introduction/hook, step-by-step teaching flow, in-class activities, examples, and a short recap/summary.
**Constraints:** Must fit within a [40/60]-minute class period; language must match the comprehension level of the target grade.
**Output Format:** A structured lesson plan with clear time-stamped sections and headings.
**Evaluation Criteria:** Clarity, logical flow from simple to complex, and practical usability in a real classroom.

---

### 2. Quiz
**Role:** You are a subject-matter expert and assessment designer.
**Objective:** Create a [number]-question quiz on [topic] to test student understanding.
**Background:** The quiz will be used as a short in-class or homework assessment after teaching the topic.
**Target Audience:** [Grade level] students.
**Requirements:** Mix of question types (MCQs, short answer, true/false); difficulty progressing from easy to hard; include an answer key.
**Constraints:** Must strictly contain [number] questions; no ambiguous or trick questions.
**Output Format:** Numbered quiz questions followed by a separate, clearly labeled answer key.
**Evaluation Criteria:** Questions must accurately test the intended concept and be free of ambiguity.

---

### 3. Homework
**Role:** You are a subject teacher assigning practice work.
**Objective:** Create a homework assignment on [topic] to reinforce classroom learning.
**Background:** Students have just completed a lesson on this topic and need independent practice.
**Target Audience:** [Grade level] students.
**Requirements:** Include a range of question difficulty, cover all sub-topics taught, and provide brief instructions for each section.
**Constraints:** Should be completable within [X] minutes/hours without additional teacher supervision.
**Output Format:** A clearly sectioned homework sheet with instructions and numbered questions.
**Evaluation Criteria:** Questions must reinforce (not exceed) what was taught in class, with appropriate difficulty progression.

---

### 4. Worksheet
**Role:** You are an instructional content designer.
**Objective:** Create a practice worksheet on [topic] for skill reinforcement.
**Background:** The worksheet will be used for either classroom practice or self-study.
**Target Audience:** [Grade level] students.
**Requirements:** Include a short concept recap, guided examples, and practice problems with increasing difficulty.
**Constraints:** Keep to one page/section per sub-topic; avoid overly complex problems not yet covered.
**Output Format:** A structured worksheet with concept summary, examples, and practice questions (answer key optional).
**Evaluation Criteria:** Should build confidence through guided practice before independent problem-solving.

---

### 5. Parent Communication
**Role:** You are a class teacher drafting communication for parents.
**Objective:** Write a clear, professional message to parents about [topic — e.g., student progress, upcoming event, concern].
**Background:** This communication will be sent via school app/email to parents of students in [grade/class].
**Target Audience:** Parents/guardians of school students.
**Requirements:** Polite, clear, and informative tone; include relevant details (dates, actions needed, contact info).
**Constraints:** Keep it concise (under 150 words); avoid technical/education jargon.
**Output Format:** A ready-to-send message (email or notice format) with a clear subject line.
**Evaluation Criteria:** Message must be unambiguous, respectful, and actionable for parents.

